# LLM abstraction layer

## Rule
LLM calls go through a provider abstraction (`LiteLLMProvider` / `model_client.py` / equivalent). Never call the vendor SDK (`openai`, `google.generativeai`, `anthropic`, `azure-openai`) directly from feature code.

## Why
rate-agent, qa-agent, and quote-ai-backend already centralize vendor routing behind LiteLLM / `model_client.py`. The abstraction owns: model selection, per-vendor headers, retry semantics, token accounting, structured logging. Direct SDK calls bypass all of it and lock feature code to a single vendor.

## Constraints
- A single module per service owns LLM config (model name, temperature, base URL, key fetching).
- Feature code calls the abstraction with role-tagged messages; it does not construct vendor-specific request bodies.
- Vendor upgrades happen in the abstraction; feature code does not change.
- `prompt-review-agent` verifies new code goes through the abstraction; direct SDK imports in feature paths block the review gate.

## Examples

### Good (Python)
```python
from llm.client import chat

resp = chat(messages=[...], model=Model.DEFAULT, max_tokens=8000)
```

### Bad
```python
from openai import OpenAI
client = OpenAI()
resp = client.chat.completions.create(...)  # direct SDK; bypasses abstraction
```

